  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Preface to Bidding Farewell to Jeon Wogun, Emissary to the Eastern Region
  author: Lee Gyeongbo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I have heard it said that among all the mountains and waters of this world, those of the Eastern Region are the most sublime and beautiful. The clustered stones of Geumran and its vermillion caves, the Three-Day Port of Goseong, the Naksan of Yeongryeong—though I have never beheld the legendary isles of Penglai and Fangzhang, I cannot imagine they could surpass these wonders. Long have I dreamed that to glimpse them even once would be worth dying without regret. Yet I remain entangled in worldly affairs, the thousand-li journey stretches endlessly before me, and I can only gaze sorrowfully eastward, my heart heavy with longing.

    Now you depart, bearing the dragon scepter that blazes with imperial splendor, your light traveling garments fluttering, galloping upon swift steeds as though wings sprouted from your sides and you soared beyond the six directions of heaven itself—stirring in us an envy that knows no bounds. We climb the heights and grasp your sleeves, pouring wine with our own hands in farewell. Yet this parting shall not be long. Why then need we shed tears so freely?

    I imagine that each mountain you encounter, each stream you cross, will draw your thoughts back to me. Should you find no way to seal the clear waters and crimson peaks within a letter to send home, let poetry capture them instead. Commit your visions to verse and send them upon the wind, so that the mountains and waters of the Eastern Sea may materialize vividly before my eyes. In this way, my longing shall be satisfied. What need then for me to behold them in person?

    Our friends have composed their poems. I offer this preface to stand at their head.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The Eastern Region (關東) refers to the mountainous territories of the Korean peninsula, particularly the Diamond Mountains region celebrated in East Asian literature.
  - key: ''
    value: Penglai (蓬萊) and Fangzhang (方丈) are legendary paradises from Chinese Daoist tradition, representing unattainable ideals of natural perfection.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'dragon sceptel' (龍節) and 'imperial splendor' (皇華) are metaphors for official authority and dignified diplomatic mission.
  - key: ''
    value: This is a preface to a collection of poems written by Lee Gyeongbo's circle to honor Jeon Wogun's departure on an official embassy to the east.
